<ns6:section xmlns:ns6="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.concepts.developmentProcess.openSource.licenses.bsdLicense">

  <ns7:title xmlns:ns7="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Unlimited commercial and non-commercial use via the BSD license</ns7:title>
  <ns8:para xmlns:ns8="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    The BSD license was originally used for BSD Unix, which was developed by the University of
    California at Berkeley. The license or adoptions of it have been used since for many other open-
    source applications, including Apache web server and XFree86. The BSD license is often regarded
    as containing the minimal features of any open-source license. The core features of the BSD
    license are 
    <ns9:itemizedlist xmlns:ns9="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
      <ns10:listitem xmlns:ns10="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns11:para xmlns:ns11="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        a protection for developers against lawsuits for damages due to the use of the application,
      </ns11:para></ns10:listitem>
      <ns12:listitem xmlns:ns12="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns13:para xmlns:ns13="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        explicit rights to be able to make unlimited copies and use the system and its source,
      </ns13:para></ns12:listitem>
      <ns14:listitem xmlns:ns14="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns15:para xmlns:ns15="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
         the requirement that the copyright notices are retained when redistributing the application 
         in any form,
      </ns15:para></ns14:listitem>
      <ns16:listitem xmlns:ns16="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns17:para xmlns:ns17="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        and a requirement that developers are credited in advertising material.
      </ns17:para></ns16:listitem>
    </ns9:itemizedlist>
    The BSD license is academic in nature in that it ensures that the sources of information are 
    duely credited, but granting unlimited commercial use of the software.   
  </ns8:para>
</ns6:section>